00:15:27.192 --> 00:15:30.812
only on safety and efficacy, but really scalability, speed,

258
00:15:31.272 --> 00:15:35.132
cost, and access. And I think you'll hear from the other panelists

259
00:15:35.872 --> 00:15:39.472
the opportunities there for both allogeneic and in vivo.

260
00:15:40.912 --> 00:15:44.352
With respect to autologous manufacturing,

261
00:15:44.792 --> 00:15:47.992
the idea of being able to manufacture these cells more

262
00:15:48.112 --> 00:15:52.012
rapidly with automated platforms and

263
00:15:52.112 --> 00:15:52.692
even more

264
00:15:53.532 --> 00:15:56.652
flexible regulatory frameworks, I think will be key

265
00:15:56.712 --> 00:15:58.572
enablers. And so,

266
00:16:00.192 --> 00:16:04.072
we'll see where the field goes. I think what will be interesting

267
00:16:04.132 --> 00:16:08.012
is really how these approaches complement each

268
00:16:08.092 --> 00:16:10.812
other in distinct disease settings.

269
00:16:11.362 --> 00:16:15.072
And so with this, I'd like to pass off the

270
00:16:15.212 --> 00:16:18.292
baton to my colleague and panelist,

271
00:16:18.972 --> 00:16:21.892
Zachary Roberts, to talk about allogeneic

272
00:16:22.952 --> 00:16:24.772
cell therapy. Thank you very much.

273
00:16:33.912 --> 00:16:37.472
Thanks very much, Dr. Brown, and thanks everybody for carving out a bit of time

274
00:16:37.512 --> 00:16:38.952
here towards the end of the conference.

275
00:16:39.752 --> 00:16:42.012
They clearly saved the best for last.

276
00:16:43.392 --> 00:16:46.852
Okay, so I'm going to dive into allogeneic cell therapy. As Dr.

277
00:16:47.092 --> 00:16:50.952
Brown pointed out, there is clearly a growing need for

278
00:16:51.772 --> 00:16:55.652
a variety of new indications coming online for allogeneic

279
00:16:55.732 --> 00:16:58.232
cell therapy or for cell therapy in general.

280
00:16:58.372 --> 00:16:59.092
And we believe that

281
00:17:00.052 --> 00:17:03.932
having an allogeneic platform is going to be critical to achieving that

282
00:17:03.972 --> 00:17:04.492
demand.

283
00:17:06.093 --> 00:17:09.272
But before we get there, of course, there are clear

284
00:17:09.853 --> 00:17:13.833
requirements for any new modality coming online, such as allogeneic

285
00:17:13.873 --> 00:17:17.613
cell therapy, that it has to be an improvement over what's already available.

286
00:17:17.633 --> 00:17:21.242
And so I think of these as really the foundational benefits as

287
00:17:21.732 --> 00:17:25.613
what is required in an aspirational way for a

288
00:17:25.712 --> 00:17:28.172
new platform like allogeneic cell therapy

289
00:17:28.212 --> 00:17:32.100
manufacturingTo replace the proven efficacy and safety

290
00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:34.860
that Dr. Brown highlighted with the autologous product.

291
00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:36.560
So first of all, they have to be useful.

292
00:17:36.940 --> 00:17:40.880
They have to provide some clinical utility, and really focusing here on efficacy.

293
00:17:41.400 --> 00:17:45.340
There has to be a durable response in whichever disease we're talking

294
00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:49.340
about with the one-time administration that is afforded by the

295
00:17:49.350 --> 00:17:53.210
autologous products, and we have to start the therapy with the intent

296
00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:56.950
to cure. We can't be eroding the efficacy signal by

297
00:17:56.960 --> 00:17:59.600
moving from an autologous platform to an allogeneic one.

298
00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:02.800
We have to improve the patient accessibility.

299
00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:04.400
So not only does this mean

300
00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:09.180
a more immediately available product for infusion when the patient

301
00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:12.760
needs it, without the need for leukapheresis and manufacturing,

302
00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:17.660
but also it has to be safe. It has to be something that can be administered

303
00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:18.780
not just in

304
00:18:19.780 --> 00:18:23.740
well-connected, well-run academic centers with a bunch of experience in an

305
00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:27.640
autologous, but really, how do we get outside of the

306
00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:31.540
academic centers and into the community where, as it applies to cancer,

307
00:18:31.800 --> 00:18:35.640
80% of patients with cancer are managed fully in the community setting

308
00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:39.120
and really they don't have access to autologous CAR T.

309
00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:43.160
So can we improve access with a new platform like

310
00:18:43.220 --> 00:18:43.900
allogeneic?

311
00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:48.070
And then finally, of course, we have to be able to do this at scale.

312
00:18:48.800 --> 00:18:52.720
At Allogene, our current manufacturing would enable us to produce 30,000 to

313
00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:57.020
60,000 doses of cell therapies per year.

314
00:18:57.820 --> 00:19:01.620
The range there is dependent on which cells, which product we're

315
00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:05.530
using, and what the cell dose is. The cost of goods manufactured in

316
00:19:05.540 --> 00:19:09.460
this context is as little as under 10,000 per dose and

317
00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:11.660
up to 20, again, depending on the product.

318
00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:15.840
Ideally, this would be used and ordered using a simplified

319
00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:19.400
mechanism through an EHR, without

320
00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:23.219
approaching this like a procedure such as a bone marrow transplant.

321
00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:26.820
And of course, it would need broad payer acceptance and utilization in health

322
00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:27.360
systems.

323
00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:31.980
But before we get to any of those aspirational statements, we really need to talk

324
00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:35.680
about some basic immunobiology. I'll be speaking

325
00:19:35.720 --> 00:19:39.360
mostly today about allogeneic CAR T cells, but of course, there are other

326
00:19:39.420 --> 00:19:41.620
manufacturing platforms as well.

327
00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:45.300
But it all boils down to can we do this safe and efficaciously?

328
00:19:45.560 --> 00:19:49.320
And really that begins with graft versus host disease and the opposite, host

329
00:19:49.360 --> 00:19:52.960
versus graft. Do these allogeneic healthy donor-derived products

330
00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:56.700
recognize the recipient as foreign, causing GvHD?

331
00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:56.950
Or

332
00:19:57.760 --> 00:20:01.390
does the immune-attacked recipient recognize the

333
00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:05.340
incoming CAR T cells as foreign and reject them before they can render

334
00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:06.089
their efficacy?

335
00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:10.540
So depending on, you have to forgive me for the

336
00:20:11.260 --> 00:20:15.160
joke here about chassis, but I couldn't pass up the opportunity to make a

337
00:20:15.220 --> 00:20:19.160
CAR T joke, but depending on which cell therapy platform

338
00:20:19.220 --> 00:20:22.399
you use, you have different pros and cons.

339
00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:26.480
So with NK cells, and Dr. Rezvani gave a wonderful talk just a few hours ago about

340
00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:30.300
all the work she's doing at MD Anderson on NK cells.

341
00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:32.560
She's absolutely correct. They have the

342
00:20:33.820 --> 00:20:37.580
off-the-shelf benefit of having little to no GvHD

343
00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:39.780
risk. They're easy to manufacture.

344
00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:44.140
However, their short persistence requires armoring and

345
00:20:44.180 --> 00:20:47.980
sometimes repeat dosing. They also have native tumor targeting

346
00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.900
abilities, so you get two for one with the CAR plus the endogenous

347
00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:53.860
native tumor targeting capabilities.

348
00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:56.400
The same applies to gamma delta T cells.

349
00:20:56.760 --> 00:20:59.200
They have intrinsic tumor targeting capabilities.

350
00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:02.670
However, they're extremely rare in the peripheral blood, which makes their

351
00:21:03.340 --> 00:21:04.780
manufacturing very difficult.

352
00:21:05.900 --> 00:21:09.800
And then finally, on the right-hand side, iPSC derived T or

353
00:21:09.840 --> 00:21:13.540
NK cells, often sometimes regarded as the holy grail of

354
00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:17.300
allogeneic cell therapy because you get large doses of master cell

355
00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:21.200
banks, you can make thousands of doses of cells from those banks, so you get

356
00:21:21.240 --> 00:21:23.060
manufacturing consistency and scale.

357
00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:27.060
However, as the cartoon illustrates, this can be quite lengthy and complex

358
00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:27.890
manufacturing.

359
00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:32.530
So today I'm going to be focusing on CAR T cells, and the story begins about 10

360
00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:36.480
years ago with one of the very first examples of

361
00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:40.460
using healthy donor-derived mature T cells as a

362
00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:44.460
CAR T manufacturing substrate, and these investigators in England

363
00:21:45.060 --> 00:21:49.020
introduced a fairly garden variety CAR construct here

364
00:21:49.059 --> 00:21:53.040
with a CD19 targeting moiety and then a 4-1BB co-stimulatory domain.

365
00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:57.500
They also did some gene editing to make these CARs safe by

366
00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:01.420
eliminating TCR expression through disruption of the TRAC locus with TALEN

367
00:22:01.500 --> 00:22:05.430
gene editing, and they also disrupted the CD52 locus, which you'll

368
00:22:05.460 --> 00:22:07.140
see is a recurring theme in my talk.

369
00:22:07.700 --> 00:22:11.100
The manufacturing process was fairly straightforward, shown in the middle, and on

370
00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:14.060
the right-hand side, these are the cells that come out of the end of that

371
00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:17.740
manufacturing process. High CAR positivity, low TCR

372
00:22:17.780 --> 00:22:20.920
expression, though not zero, which is what that upper red box on the right-hand

373
00:22:20.960 --> 00:22:24.840
side is meant to convey here. And then also a substantial

374
00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:27.400
fraction of these cells being CD52 negative.

375
00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:32.140
So they treated two infants with this construct, and they found that

376
00:22:33.540 --> 00:22:37.020
they were largely safe, and the first baby that was treated with the

377
00:22:37.040 --> 00:22:40.960
refractory B-ALL did have some GvHD, which

378
00:22:41.020 --> 00:22:44.300
was attributed to that residual TCR positive

379
00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:47.390
CD52 negative population I pointed out on the previous slide,

380
00:22:48.260 --> 00:22:51.600
that required them to treat with first topical steroids, then actually

381
00:22:52.060 --> 00:22:55.980
trigger the kill switch, which is included in this construct, and then take this

382
00:22:56.620 --> 00:23:00.260
infant to a second allograft, shown here as allo

383
00:23:00.360 --> 00:23:01.000
SCT2.

384
00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:05.200
They were quite encouraged, and I think reasonably so, by the efficacy as

385
00:23:05.220 --> 00:23:07.300
illustrated in the MRD assessment in this baby,

386
00:23:08.180 --> 00:23:12.100
who cleared their MRD by day 28. So

387
00:23:12.440 --> 00:23:16.300
obviously a great proof of concept here that these cells manufactured from

388
00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:18.260
healthy donors can bring efficacy

389
00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:21.680
with some manageable safety

390
00:23:22.980 --> 00:23:26.892
with that skin GvHD.However, when

391
00:23:26.912 --> 00:23:30.612
they looked at the expansion kinetics of

392
00:23:30.732 --> 00:23:32.612
these infused cells,

393
00:23:33.432 --> 00:23:37.272
they realized that there was a whole future of work on

394
00:23:37.692 --> 00:23:40.522
host versus graft to be done. So on the first

395
00:23:41.392 --> 00:23:45.272
patient that was treated, as shown on the left, with fairly limited CAR

396
00:23:45.312 --> 00:23:48.712
T expansion. There was some persistence out to that second allograft.

397
00:23:49.052 --> 00:23:52.752
However, we didn't see the typical large expansion within the

398
00:23:52.792 --> 00:23:56.532
days following that we had seen with axicel and lysocel by this

399
00:23:56.572 --> 00:24:00.352
point. The second infant that was treated, who similarly had a great

400
00:24:00.392 --> 00:24:03.682
clinical outcome, they increased the dose of

401
00:24:04.612 --> 00:24:08.362
cytotoxic chemotherapy, which corresponded to a much larger

402
00:24:08.372 --> 00:24:12.152
initial burst of CAR T-cell expansion in vivo.

403
00:24:12.172 --> 00:24:14.462
However, these were rapidly cleared from circulation.

404
00:24:14.492 --> 00:24:18.292
So, with these first two patients, we realized that we had a persistence

405
00:24:18.352 --> 00:24:19.712
issue that we needed to surmount.

406
00:24:20.972 --> 00:24:24.712
At Allogene, we have taken this CD52 concept and really run with it.

407
00:24:24.792 --> 00:24:28.432
The idea behind it is once you've knocked CD52 out of your CAR

408
00:24:28.452 --> 00:24:30.792
T-cell, as we've done in our lead program here, celma-cel,

409
00:24:31.792 --> 00:24:35.342
administration of a CD52 monoclonal antibody would

410
00:24:35.372 --> 00:24:37.932
create a preferential impact,

411
00:24:39.032 --> 00:24:42.752
whereby the host T-cells would be eliminated through the

412
00:24:42.792 --> 00:24:46.752
CD52 monoclonal, whereas the CAR T-cells would be spared, opening

413
00:24:46.852 --> 00:24:50.552
a window of persistence. And indeed, in our Phase 1 experience in large

414
00:24:50.572 --> 00:24:54.092
B-cell lymphoma, we found that patients with the highest exposure to

415
00:24:54.132 --> 00:24:58.092
alo-647, which is our alemtuzumab-like molecule,

416
00:24:58.942 --> 00:25:02.902
had the best CAR T-cell expansion and persistence as assessed by AUC28.

417
00:25:03.372 --> 00:25:07.052
And conversely, those with the lowest exposure to the CD52 had

418
00:25:07.092 --> 00:25:10.072
the lowest, AUC28.

419
00:25:11.372 --> 00:25:14.752
This idea of deepening lymphodepletion to improve allo CAR T

420
00:25:14.812 --> 00:25:18.752
expansion persistence has been done by others as well, even

421
00:25:18.792 --> 00:25:22.492
without the CD52. And so here is an example of a peer

422
00:25:22.512 --> 00:25:26.292
company of ours, Caribou, with a CB-011

423
00:25:26.312 --> 00:25:30.212
product for myeloma. They've enhanced the engineering a little

424
00:25:30.232 --> 00:25:34.072
bit to cloak these cells by eliminating beta-2 microglobulin,

425
00:25:34.112 --> 00:25:37.972
thereby eliminating class I expression, and they've replaced it with

426
00:25:38.032 --> 00:25:41.712
a transgenic HLA-E to prevent NK-mediated

427
00:25:41.872 --> 00:25:45.672
elimination. But even with those cloaking additions to this

428
00:25:45.892 --> 00:25:49.152
product, you can clearly see a differential on expansion

429
00:25:49.872 --> 00:25:53.632
when you go from 300 milligrams per meter squared of Cytoxan to 500.

430
00:25:54.052 --> 00:25:57.822
So again, suggesting that the depth of lymphodepletion of these allo recipients

431
00:25:58.232 --> 00:26:00.142
impacts the CAR T-cell persistence.

432
00:26:01.512 --> 00:26:04.352
In our hands, in relapse refractory LBCL, the

433
00:26:04.392 --> 00:26:08.312
CD52 plus FC regimen has worked quite

434
00:26:08.381 --> 00:26:12.172
well. Here is a safety from a fairly extensive Phase

435
00:26:12.412 --> 00:26:16.272
1 program that was published last year in JCO, showing good tolerability, which

436
00:26:16.332 --> 00:26:19.612
is emblematic of allogeneic cell products.

437
00:26:20.192 --> 00:26:24.072
No high-grade CRS or ICANS. I'll highlight here, no GVHD.

438
00:26:24.132 --> 00:26:28.082
And by the way, we've treated over 200 patients across multiple programs,

439
00:26:28.252 --> 00:26:32.212
and with the TCR editing that I highlighted, we have

440
00:26:32.272 --> 00:26:35.612
not seen a case of confirmed GVHD. That seemed to have been isolated to that first

441
00:26:35.632 --> 00:26:38.412
patient treated that I highlighted a moment ago.

442
00:26:39.772 --> 00:26:43.452
Efficacy-wise, again, thinking about those must-haves that I

443
00:26:43.492 --> 00:26:47.272
highlighted at the beginning of the talk, we saw good efficacy with this

444
00:26:47.532 --> 00:26:50.992
product, I would say comparable to what we see with autologous CAR

445
00:26:51.012 --> 00:26:54.772
T in a similar patient population with a 67% overall

446
00:26:54.792 --> 00:26:56.752
response rate in the Phase 2 regimen.

447
00:26:57.152 --> 00:27:00.972
Almost all of those responses were complete with good durability and

448
00:27:01.052 --> 00:27:01.952
overall survival.

449
00:27:04.132 --> 00:27:07.732
Other approaches to enhancing persistence and expansion of allo CAR T

450
00:27:08.752 --> 00:27:12.582
are doubling down on the complex engineering to further cloak and

451
00:27:12.632 --> 00:27:14.282
enhance the performance of the cells.

452
00:27:14.992 --> 00:27:18.612
So eliminating Class I, as I pointed out, is being

453
00:27:18.632 --> 00:27:21.512
done widely, but you can also eliminate Class II.

454
00:27:22.432 --> 00:27:26.332
You can also disrupt genes that induce exhaustion of the CAR T-cell, such

455
00:27:26.372 --> 00:27:30.032
as PD-1. This strategy has been undertaken by

456
00:27:30.092 --> 00:27:33.792
a group in China, and they've treated three autoimmune

457
00:27:33.932 --> 00:27:37.832
patients with this complex engineered product,

458
00:27:38.272 --> 00:27:40.572
and they've seen significantly improved

459
00:27:41.672 --> 00:27:45.011
expansion and persistence in these patients going out now several months.

460
00:27:46.511 --> 00:27:50.342
So what I'll talk about now, though, is reframing how we think about expansion and

461
00:27:50.392 --> 00:27:52.292
persistence with allo CAR T. And

462
00:27:53.252 --> 00:27:56.892
I think of this really as an in vivo effector-to-target

463
00:27:57.012 --> 00:28:00.592
experiment. And really what we want to do is optimize that ratio.

464
00:28:01.152 --> 00:28:04.672
Instead of just driving the highest expansion and the longest

465
00:28:04.712 --> 00:28:08.162
persistence, which itself brings both acute and chronic toxicities,

466
00:28:08.712 --> 00:28:12.542
if we can tailor the expansion to the clinical scenario, that might be a better

467
00:28:12.612 --> 00:28:14.492
way to go about doing that. And

468
00:28:15.792 --> 00:28:18.372
so what do I mean by that? Well, first, talking about

469
00:28:20.492 --> 00:28:24.352
what we know about disease burden and response and toxicity in

470
00:28:24.392 --> 00:28:28.262
CAR T-cells, we've known for some time, and the patients who have low

471
00:28:28.332 --> 00:28:31.752
disease burden at the time of their CAR T-cell infusion tend to do better from both

472
00:28:31.792 --> 00:28:33.502
an efficacy and a safety perspective.

473
00:28:34.052 --> 00:28:37.922
And this is, on the left, is data from axicel that was published a

474
00:28:37.952 --> 00:28:41.732
few years ago, showing that the greater your baseline

475
00:28:41.832 --> 00:28:45.752
tumor burden, the less likely you are to have a durable response and the

476
00:28:45.772 --> 00:28:49.372
more likely you are to have a high-grade neurotoxicity event.

477
00:28:49.392 --> 00:28:53.072
And in our hands, in this Phase 1 experience, we also saw in a subgroup analysis

478
00:28:53.112 --> 00:28:57.072
that patients with low disease burden at the time of celma-cel infusion did

479
00:28:57.112 --> 00:29:00.832
much better, as assessed by normal baseline LDH

480
00:29:00.912 --> 00:29:04.752
or low disease burden as assessed by CT, in which we saw an

481
00:29:04.912 --> 00:29:07.412
82% or 100% complete remission rate,

482
00:29:07.452 --> 00:29:11.356
respectively.So how do we take this observation and layer it

483
00:29:11.396 --> 00:29:14.276
onto a clinical trial? And so coming back to LBCL,

484
00:29:15.136 --> 00:29:18.876
we have treated LBCL patients the same way for about 25 years.

485
00:29:18.936 --> 00:29:22.546
At diagnosis, almost everybody gets R-CHOP or some variant

486
00:29:22.676 --> 00:29:26.556
thereof. And about 90% of the patients who are treated in this way

487
00:29:26.616 --> 00:29:29.716
achieve a remission. Most of those tend to be complete remissions.

488
00:29:30.456 --> 00:29:33.976
The small minority of patients who have a

489
00:29:34.176 --> 00:29:37.496
primary progressive disease after frontline treatment go straight onto

490
00:29:37.536 --> 00:29:41.226
salvage. But after these 90% of

491
00:29:41.296 --> 00:29:44.976
patients achieve a remission, we essentially embark upon a

492
00:29:45.036 --> 00:29:48.616
surveillance program where we watch and wait for the disease to recur.

493
00:29:48.656 --> 00:29:52.496
And after several years, if your lymphoma hasn't come back, we declare you

494
00:29:52.556 --> 00:29:55.696
cured, and off you go.

495
00:29:56.016 --> 00:29:59.816
However, there are about a third of these patients who, during

496
00:29:59.826 --> 00:30:03.296
that period of follow-up, will actually experience a disease recurrence.

497
00:30:04.056 --> 00:30:07.116
And under the current treatment paradigm, we don't really know who is who.

498
00:30:08.556 --> 00:30:11.916
However, in the last several years, there's been quite a lot of work done on

499
00:30:11.956 --> 00:30:15.476
minimal residual disease, both in LBCL and of course beyond.

500
00:30:16.056 --> 00:30:19.406
And the data that's on the screen right now is data from one of our

501
00:30:19.476 --> 00:30:23.276
collaborators, Foresight Diagnostics, who was recently acquired by Natera,

502
00:30:23.776 --> 00:30:27.376
who is developing an ultrasensitive ctDNA-based

503
00:30:27.596 --> 00:30:31.316
MRD test. And when this test is performed at the end of frontline

504
00:30:31.416 --> 00:30:31.756
treatment,

505
00:30:32.656 --> 00:30:36.636
we can really parse these patients out into two groups, those who are likely to be

506
00:30:36.736 --> 00:30:39.336
cured, that's the blue line. These are folks who are

507
00:30:39.596 --> 00:30:42.996
ctDNA undetectable at the end of frontline treatment.

508
00:30:43.526 --> 00:30:46.895
And those who have residual disease but are in a clinical remission, are very

509
00:30:46.936 --> 00:30:50.716
likely to experience disease progression, usually within the first six to 12

510
00:30:50.756 --> 00:30:51.076
months.

511
00:30:52.136 --> 00:30:55.356
We can also quantify the disease carefully using these tests.

512
00:30:55.386 --> 00:30:58.756
And what we've found is that there's about a 200-fold lower disease

513
00:30:58.776 --> 00:31:02.766
burden at the end of therapy in an MRD positive patient as compared

514
00:31:02.816 --> 00:31:06.756
to the disease burden at diagnosis or at the time

515
00:31:06.816 --> 00:31:10.776
of relapse. So really what we are able to do with this MRD

516
00:31:10.836 --> 00:31:14.636
test is zero in on those patients with the lowest imaginable disease burden.

517
00:31:15.236 --> 00:31:19.036
In my effector-to-target ratio construct, these are the patients with the

518
00:31:19.136 --> 00:31:21.196
lowest target burden that we can think of.

519
00:31:22.396 --> 00:31:25.456
So we saw an opportunity to run a clinical trial here, which we have started.

520
00:31:25.716 --> 00:31:29.516
It's called ALPHA III. This is just those patients I just described,

521
00:31:29.676 --> 00:31:33.516
patients who are in remission, but are MRD positive at the end of treatment.

522
00:31:33.596 --> 00:31:37.446
And we're randomizing these patients to either observation, which is the current

523
00:31:37.496 --> 00:31:39.976
standard of care, or a dose of consolidation cemasil.

524
00:31:40.996 --> 00:31:43.276
EFS is the primary endpoint of this trial.

525
00:31:43.696 --> 00:31:45.656
Secondary endpoints are shown on the bottom right.

526
00:31:46.936 --> 00:31:49.336
The target enrollment is 220 patients.

527
00:31:49.396 --> 00:31:53.166
We're currently open in about 60 centers here in North America and

528
00:31:53.216 --> 00:31:56.836
recently just activating sites in the Asia-Pacific region.

529
00:31:57.676 --> 00:31:58.816
As luck would have it, we just

530
00:31:59.636 --> 00:32:03.596
last week performed this very first interim

531
00:32:03.636 --> 00:32:07.476
look at the data that we call a futility analysis, which I'll take you through now.

532
00:32:08.456 --> 00:32:12.116
We examined MRD clearance. So as a reminder, all these patients are MRD positive

533
00:32:12.156 --> 00:32:16.056
coming into the study. But we assessed whether a

534
00:32:16.076 --> 00:32:20.036
dose of consolidation cemasil would eradicate that

535
00:32:20.136 --> 00:32:24.036
MRD in these patients. So what we found that in almost 60% of the patients who

536
00:32:24.076 --> 00:32:26.376
were randomized into the cemasil arm,

537
00:32:27.696 --> 00:32:31.656
emerged MRD negative as compared to 16.7% in the

538
00:32:31.716 --> 00:32:35.616
observation arm. And this change in ctDNA happened very quickly.

539
00:32:35.696 --> 00:32:39.156
So the first time we looked after these patients are randomized is at day 45.

540
00:32:39.716 --> 00:32:43.656
And at that time, we saw a median decrease of about 98% of

541
00:32:43.696 --> 00:32:47.196
the circulating tumor DNA in the patients who received cemasil versus a

542
00:32:47.336 --> 00:32:51.016
26.6% increase in the patients who were observed, which is, of course,

543
00:32:51.436 --> 00:32:54.776
what we would expect if we leave these MRD positive patients alone.

544
00:32:56.896 --> 00:33:00.876
As interesting about as the efficacy is the safety, and

545
00:33:00.916 --> 00:33:03.866
again, thinking about this E to T ratio concept.

546
00:33:04.316 --> 00:33:07.696
We saw no cases of CRS. We saw no cases of ICANS.

547
00:33:07.816 --> 00:33:11.236
No tocilizumab or steroids were given to any of these patients.

548
00:33:11.276 --> 00:33:12.696
Of course, no GVHD.

549
00:33:13.516 --> 00:33:16.036
Infections were balanced in the two arms.

550
00:33:16.576 --> 00:33:17.816
We did see slightly more

551
00:33:19.096 --> 00:33:23.006
other neurologic events that were largely attributed to the FC regimen that

552
00:33:23.036 --> 00:33:25.006
the patients in the cemasil arm got.

553
00:33:25.716 --> 00:33:28.396
And importantly, none of these patients were admitted to the hospital for

554
00:33:28.416 --> 00:33:32.256
management of side effects. And as I come back to

555
00:33:32.296 --> 00:33:35.086
those aspirational themes at the beginning of the talk,

556
00:33:36.296 --> 00:33:38.786
can we get this out of academic centers and into the community?

557
00:33:38.886 --> 00:33:42.776
A third of the patients who were treated with cemasil were treated in community

558
00:33:42.836 --> 00:33:46.656
oncology practices, many of which have never given a single dose of CAR T

559
00:33:46.676 --> 00:33:47.006
before.

560
00:33:48.286 --> 00:33:51.936
So getting this access out of academia and into the community where

561
00:33:52.056 --> 00:33:55.956
80% of these patients are treated is a major strategic imperative of any

562
00:33:55.976 --> 00:33:57.376
allogeneic platform.

563
00:33:58.476 --> 00:34:02.456
In the last few minutes, I'm going to shift gears and talk about another way to

564
00:34:02.496 --> 00:34:03.936
achieve optimal E to T.

565
00:34:04.816 --> 00:34:08.736
In the case of the RCC program, renal cell carcinoma, the target

566
00:34:08.796 --> 00:34:11.656
ratio or the target burden in these patients is quite a bit higher.

567
00:34:11.696 --> 00:34:14.136
These are metastatic solid tumor patients.

568
00:34:14.736 --> 00:34:18.036
And the theme of this last few slides

569
00:34:18.336 --> 00:34:22.276
is more about a good offense being the best

570
00:34:22.286 --> 00:34:25.596
defense in terms of allogeneic rejection.

571
00:34:25.917 --> 00:34:29.496
And so I'll be talking a little bit about the CD70 biology we call the dagger,

572
00:34:30.336 --> 00:34:33.937
and we've incorporated this dagger of technology into our next

573
00:34:33.976 --> 00:34:37.056
generation platform, which is ALO329, which we're developing for

574
00:34:37.116 --> 00:34:40.732
autoimmunity.So early on, we discovered that

575
00:34:41.072 --> 00:34:44.402
not all CD70-targeting CARs were created equal.

576
00:34:44.892 --> 00:34:46.892
CD70 is a very interesting target.

577
00:34:47.152 --> 00:34:51.013
Not only is it expressed highly in RCC and other solid tumors and heme

578
00:34:51.022 --> 00:34:54.852
malignancies, but it's also an activation marker for T cells, and it's

579
00:34:54.892 --> 00:34:58.872
upregulated when a T cell engages its target, be that

580
00:34:59.852 --> 00:35:03.512
an allogeneic CAR T cell or an

581
00:35:03.532 --> 00:35:05.152
infectious particle or what have you.

582
00:35:05.952 --> 00:35:08.052
And so that sets up a little bit of a problem.

583
00:35:08.152 --> 00:35:11.892
So as you're manufacturing CD70 CAR T cells, the CD70 CAR

584
00:35:11.932 --> 00:35:15.612
expressed on the T cell will recognize the CD70 on

585
00:35:15.652 --> 00:35:18.732
neighboring CAR T cells, inducing something that we call fratricide.

586
00:35:19.332 --> 00:35:21.132
However, if we design the

587
00:35:22.652 --> 00:35:26.192
CAR T cell to target membrane-distal epitopes in the CD70,

588
00:35:26.692 --> 00:35:30.632
we can actually establish what we've called cis-masking, where the CAR will

589
00:35:30.692 --> 00:35:34.312
actually block the CD70 on the CAR T cell, thus

590
00:35:34.452 --> 00:35:38.332
preventing neighboring CAR T cells from engaging the CD70 on

591
00:35:38.372 --> 00:35:41.032
that CAR. And on the right-hand side, you can see

592
00:35:41.112 --> 00:35:44.842
a difference between Class I CARs,

593
00:35:44.912 --> 00:35:48.382
which target membrane-distal epitopes, versus Class II CARs,

594
00:35:48.452 --> 00:35:50.212
which target membrane-proximal

595
00:35:51.032 --> 00:35:54.772
epitopes. And in a flow cytometry experiment, the

596
00:35:55.612 --> 00:35:56.012
CAR T

597
00:35:57.552 --> 00:36:01.382
will actually block the detection reagent from

598
00:36:01.412 --> 00:36:05.282
sensing the CD70 on these cells, thus illustrating

599
00:36:05.312 --> 00:36:06.662
this idea of cis-masking.

600
00:36:07.972 --> 00:36:11.742
So can the CD70 CAR prevent allo rejection, which is, of course, one of the things

601
00:36:11.772 --> 00:36:15.752
that we hope it will do? The experiment on the left-hand side shows that, in fact,

602
00:36:15.812 --> 00:36:19.522
it does. So when you use alloreactive host T cells

603
00:36:19.992 --> 00:36:23.752
and a CAR T cell, and you mix them together in a mixed

604
00:36:23.772 --> 00:36:27.332
lymphocyte reaction, non-transduced CAR T cells will

605
00:36:27.432 --> 00:36:30.912
stimulate an allo reaction, and you'll see the host T cells

606
00:36:30.952 --> 00:36:33.302
upregulate CD70. Again, we expect this.

607
00:36:33.772 --> 00:36:36.232
However, in the presence of a CD70 CAR, those

608
00:36:36.552 --> 00:36:40.482
CD70-expressing fraction of host T cells are eliminated,

609
00:36:40.892 --> 00:36:44.832
and this leads to robust expansion and long-term survival

610
00:36:44.932 --> 00:36:47.452
of the CD70 CARs in a mixed lymphocyte reaction.

611
00:36:48.411 --> 00:36:51.912
This has been validated now in the clinic in the renal cell

612
00:36:51.992 --> 00:36:55.782
carcinoma program with a longstanding Phase 1

613
00:36:56.172 --> 00:37:00.052
trial called Traverse. And we have selected a

614
00:37:00.072 --> 00:37:03.492
Phase 2 regimen of 80 million CAR T cells following standard

615
00:37:03.512 --> 00:37:07.252
lymphodepletion, so no ALO-647 or CD52 monoclonal antibody

616
00:37:07.292 --> 00:37:10.392
here. And in patients with high CD70 expression, we saw

617
00:37:10.572 --> 00:37:14.512
31% durable overall response rate with kinetics

618
00:37:14.572 --> 00:37:18.392
that are consistent with what we expect of cell therapy, with rapid reduction

619
00:37:18.412 --> 00:37:22.252
in tumor burden by day 28 and durable remissions.

620
00:37:23.332 --> 00:37:27.292
But really what's interesting here is this validation of this dagger technology,

621
00:37:27.352 --> 00:37:31.292
and that the expansion and persistence of this ALO316, as shown on the table on

622
00:37:31.332 --> 00:37:35.292
the right, was really quite unprecedented, both at the level of Cmax

623
00:37:35.392 --> 00:37:36.932
as well as the AUC28,

624
00:37:38.332 --> 00:37:42.232
outpacing what we see with approved autologous products in hematologic

625
00:37:42.252 --> 00:37:46.162
malignancies. And this is really driven by this allo reaction

626
00:37:46.352 --> 00:37:49.772
by the host T cells. And this slide illustrates that further.

627
00:37:50.712 --> 00:37:54.492
First, on the left, we see great expansion, really quite unprecedented

628
00:37:54.552 --> 00:37:58.532
levels of expansion just in terms of magnitude, more in responders than in

629
00:37:58.552 --> 00:38:00.012
non-responders as we would expect.

630
00:38:00.092 --> 00:38:04.032
But in patients who have follow-up within the study, we're able to find CAR T

631
00:38:04.112 --> 00:38:07.252
cells readily in the periphery out to nine months and beyond.

632
00:38:07.892 --> 00:38:10.972
So really, we see longstanding persistence here.

633
00:38:10.992 --> 00:38:14.912
But what's even more astounding is that when we deintensified the lymphodepletion

634
00:38:14.932 --> 00:38:18.042
regimen here by removing ALO-647, we saw

635
00:38:18.072 --> 00:38:21.992
improved ALO316 expansion in the days following

636
00:38:22.032 --> 00:38:24.132
infusion. And this really, I think,

637
00:38:25.132 --> 00:38:28.872
summarizes very nicely that the magnitude of the allo

638
00:38:28.952 --> 00:38:32.692
response to the incoming CAR T cells serves as fuel to the

639
00:38:32.792 --> 00:38:35.032
allogeneic CAR T cells and in the

640
00:38:36.432 --> 00:38:40.272
rejection avoidance schema. My last data slide is here, and this

641
00:38:40.332 --> 00:38:44.212
is to illustrate that we can take this dagger effect, the CD70 CAR, and

642
00:38:44.292 --> 00:38:47.812
actually pair it with other targeting moieties, such as

643
00:38:47.992 --> 00:38:51.352
CD19 CAR, as we're doing in our autoimmune program.

644
00:38:52.092 --> 00:38:54.432
And what we've done in this experiment is model

645
00:38:55.331 --> 00:38:58.112
allo rejection in a mouse. And so we've

646
00:38:59.072 --> 00:39:02.292
simulated lymphodepletion by either giving a

647
00:39:03.552 --> 00:39:07.512
low dose of healthy donor PBMCs to these NSG mice or

648
00:39:07.532 --> 00:39:11.052
a very high dose, as if these mice had not been lymphodepleted,

649
00:39:11.132 --> 00:39:12.042
100-fold more

650
00:39:13.272 --> 00:39:16.252
potentially alloreactive healthy donor PBMCs.

651
00:39:16.292 --> 00:39:19.932
We then infuse the CAR T cells, and then we monitor for persistence at day seven

652
00:39:19.972 --> 00:39:23.832
and 14. And in the right-hand side, what we see is sort of what

653
00:39:23.892 --> 00:39:27.252
we'd expect for the CD19 CAR, and that in the absence of

654
00:39:27.272 --> 00:39:31.192
lymphodepletion, we see very little persistence of the CD19 CAR, which is,

655
00:39:31.232 --> 00:39:32.892
of course, improved when we

656
00:39:34.272 --> 00:39:38.012
simulate lymphodepletion. But we see the opposite in the

657
00:39:38.072 --> 00:39:41.992
context of a dagger-endowed CAR, in that when we leave out

658
00:39:42.032 --> 00:39:45.832
the lymphodepletion in this experiment, we see a 10 to 20-fold better

659
00:39:45.872 --> 00:39:49.692
expansion of the ALO329 as compared to when we pair

660
00:39:49.732 --> 00:39:53.192
it with a lymphodepleted mouse. So really

661
00:39:53.232 --> 00:39:56.952
paradoxical observation here showing that this

662
00:39:56.992 --> 00:40:00.912
dagger technology can really propel the expansion and persistence

663
00:40:01.412 --> 00:40:04.592
of these CAR T cells in the context of an allo response.

664
00:40:05.352 --> 00:40:09.172
So to conclude, the early safety concerns from allogeneic

665
00:40:09.232 --> 00:40:12.592
CAR T cells really focused on GBHD have largely

666
00:40:12.652 --> 00:40:15.092
been addressed by effective gene editing

667
00:40:15.932 --> 00:40:16.892
of the TRAC locus.

668
00:40:17.792 --> 00:40:20.712
We are now showing, I think, clear evidence of

669
00:40:21.692 --> 00:40:24.452
efficacy in both heme malignancy and in solid tumors.

670
00:40:25.512 --> 00:40:29.262
We can further improve upon this efficacy and safety through novel clinical trial

671
00:40:29.262 --> 00:40:32.512
design as well as next-generation product design and really

672
00:40:32.852 --> 00:40:36.552
targeting the optimal in vivo E to T ratio.

673
00:40:37.142 --> 00:40:41.112
And finally, if we're successful in the clinical trials that we have ongoing here

674
00:40:41.122 --> 00:40:45.022
and with other sponsors, the manufacturing scale and the cost of

675
00:40:45.052 --> 00:40:48.472
goods will represent a breakthrough in access to this technology for

676
00:40:48.492 --> 00:40:51.864
patients.So with that, I'll thank the patients and the investigators who have been

677
00:40:51.904 --> 00:40:54.004
with us on this journey for a long time.

678
00:40:54.244 --> 00:40:57.964
Of course, the Allogene Therapeutics team, many of whom are in the audience

679
00:40:57.984 --> 00:41:01.954
today, thanks for all the hard work in solving some of these problems.

680
00:41:02.484 --> 00:41:06.024
And to our peer companies who are carrying this baton along with us.

681
00:41:06.564 --> 00:41:06.803
Thank you.

682
00:41:13.184 --> 00:41:17.164
Thank you very much for such a fantastic talk and really

683
00:41:17.404 --> 00:41:21.144
great data. So that's wonderful. So we're going to move to in

684
00:41:21.204 --> 00:41:24.794
vivo gene editing, the hot topic of this

685
00:41:24.824 --> 00:41:28.744
session, with Dr. Alberto Diaco. So thank

686
00:41:28.844 --> 00:41:30.184
you for presenting.

687
00:41:30.764 --> 00:41:34.264
Thank you to Dr. Brown and Dr. Roberts for sharing

688
00:41:34.684 --> 00:41:38.244
the progresses in the autologous and allogeneic

689
00:41:38.724 --> 00:41:42.464
CAR T cell therapy. And I'll now share with

690
00:41:42.564 --> 00:41:42.824
you,

691
00:41:43.904 --> 00:41:47.764
I will talk about in vivo CAR T engineering, and I will also share with you a new

692
00:41:47.784 --> 00:41:51.244
technology that we developed at Tessera to approach

693
00:41:51.764 --> 00:41:55.404
the in vivo CAR T using RNA to generate permanent

694
00:41:55.864 --> 00:41:56.904
insertion of CARs.

695
00:41:59.064 --> 00:42:00.384
This is my disclosure slide.

696
00:42:01.504 --> 00:42:05.404
I don't think I need to cover any further how

697
00:42:05.424 --> 00:42:09.364
transformative ex vivo autologous, ex vivo CAR T cell therapy

698
00:42:09.374 --> 00:42:11.944
has been for hematological malignancies.

699
00:42:12.964 --> 00:42:16.914
But there are still some challenges that are being addressed,

700
00:42:17.164 --> 00:42:18.344
but they still

701
00:42:19.424 --> 00:42:23.204
pose some challenges. For example, the

702
00:42:23.404 --> 00:42:25.684
patient eligibility that

703
00:42:26.564 --> 00:42:30.414
is slowed down by the long manufacturing timelines and

704
00:42:30.484 --> 00:42:33.944
the conditioning of the patient, the limiting patient

705
00:42:34.044 --> 00:42:37.604
access to the facilities, to center and hospitals,

706
00:42:38.164 --> 00:42:41.524
and also the expensive and complex manufacturing of the product.

707
00:42:42.864 --> 00:42:46.164
I believe in vivo CAR T has the potential to overcome these

708
00:42:46.224 --> 00:42:46.904
limitations.

709
00:42:49.344 --> 00:42:52.584
So when we talk about in vivo CAR T, we're talking about reprogramming the T cells

710
00:42:52.624 --> 00:42:54.264
directly into the patient.

711
00:42:55.604 --> 00:42:59.563
In the autologous CAR T therapy, we need

712
00:42:59.584 --> 00:43:02.324
to collect cells from patient, and as Dr.

713
00:43:02.544 --> 00:43:06.364
Brown showed us before, the cells needs to be handled outside of the

714
00:43:06.384 --> 00:43:10.144
patient, and the cell needs to be transduced with vectors

715
00:43:10.444 --> 00:43:13.424
and then reinfused into the patient after conditioning.

716
00:43:14.284 --> 00:43:17.924
In the context of in vivo CAR T, you just need to have

717
00:43:18.384 --> 00:43:21.684
a vector that works at delivering specifically to T cells.

718
00:43:21.744 --> 00:43:25.644
So you just inject your vector in the patient, and the vector will find

719
00:43:25.664 --> 00:43:29.564
a T cell inside the patient to generate and engineer the CAR

720
00:43:29.604 --> 00:43:31.184
T cell.

721
00:43:33.624 --> 00:43:35.603
Here I'm highlighting four

722
00:43:37.904 --> 00:43:41.884
requirements that I believe are very important for a successful in vivo

723
00:43:41.904 --> 00:43:45.274
CAR T, especially in oncology. The first one is the targeting

724
00:43:45.364 --> 00:43:49.304
specificity, where we need to have a selective delivery to T

725
00:43:49.384 --> 00:43:49.664
cells.

726
00:43:50.544 --> 00:43:50.724
This is

727
00:43:52.604 --> 00:43:56.484
less of a problem in the ex vivo setting, as you have a limited

728
00:43:56.764 --> 00:43:59.984
number of cells that you are transducing or you're transfecting,

729
00:44:01.004 --> 00:44:04.824
making it less challenging, as

730
00:44:04.944 --> 00:44:08.544
you have less off-target cells available in your pool of cells.

731
00:44:09.004 --> 00:44:12.564
Once you go in vivo, you have potentially every cell of the body that could be

732
00:44:12.584 --> 00:44:13.294
targeted by your

733
00:44:14.124 --> 00:44:17.124
vector. Therefore, you need a good

734
00:44:18.804 --> 00:44:21.824
specificity of the vector for your T cells.

735
00:44:23.024 --> 00:44:25.084
The second bucket is engineering efficiency.

736
00:44:25.144 --> 00:44:28.664
Of course, we need sufficient efficiency in order to achieve therapeutic

